05124nam a22008055i 9780292739468DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927394687 a10.7560/7394512doi  a(DE-B1597)587084  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aSB106.B56 -- P43 2012eb 7aBUS0700102bisacsh04a6301 aPechlaner, Gabriela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCorporate Crops :bBiotechnology, Agriculture, and the Struggle for Control /cGabriela Pechlaner. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Acronyms -- tIntroduction -- t1 Agricultural Biotechnologies on the Farm and around the World -- t2 The Coming of the Third Regime? Agricultural Biotechnology Regulation in Canada and the United States -- t3 Biotechnology on the Prairies: The Rise of Canola . . . -- t4 . . . And the Fall of Wheat -- t5 Legal Offense and Defense on the Canadian Prairies -- t6 From When Cotton Was King to King Monsanto -- t7 Starting a New Regime: Training the Locals -- t8 Conclusion -- tAppendix: Log of Interviews -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiotechnology crop production area increased from 1.7 million hectares to 148 million hectares worldwide between 1996 to 2010. While genetically modified food is a contentious issue, the debates are usually limited to health and environmental concerns, ignoring the broader questions of social control that arise when food production methods become corporate-owned intellectual property. Drawing on legal documents and dozens of interviews with farmers and other stakeholders, Corporate Crops covers four case studies based around litigation between biotechnology corporations and farmers. Pechlaner investigates the extent to which the proprietary aspects of biotechnologies—from patents on seeds to a plethora of new rules and contractual obligations associated with the technologies—are reorganizing crop production. The lawsuits include patent infringement litigation launched by Monsanto against a Saskatchewan canola farmer who, in turn, claimed his crops had been involuntarily contaminated by the company’s GM technology; a class action application by two Saskatchewan organic canola farmers launched against Monsanto and Aventis (later Bayer) for the loss of their organic market due to contamination with GMOs; and two cases in Mississippi in which Monsanto sued farmers for saving seeds containing its patented GM technology. Pechlaner argues that well-funded corporate lawyers have a decided advantage over independent farmers in the courts and in creating new forms of power and control in agricultural production. Corporate Crops demonstrates the effects of this intersection between the courts and the fields where profits, not just a food supply, are reaped.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAgricultural biotechnologyxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aAgricultural biotechnologyxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aAgricultural biotechnologyzCanada. 0aAgricultural biotechnologyzUnited States. 0aFamily farmszCanada. 0aFamily farmszUnited States. 0aIntellectual propertyzCanada. 0aIntellectual propertyzUnited States. 0aPlant biotechnologyxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aPlant biotechnologyxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPlant biotechnologyzCanada. 0aPlant biotechnologyzUnited States. 0aTransgenic plantszCanada. 0aTransgenic plantszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Agribusiness.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292739468423Coveruhttps://www.degruy